05142nam a22008055i 9780231548922DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20192018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315489227 a10.7312/kran179302doi  a(DE-B1597)517749  a(OCoLC)1078417233  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0590002bisacsh04a338.2/728095362231 aKrane, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEnergy Kingdoms :bOil and Political Survival in the Persian Gulf /cJim Krane. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b17 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCenter on Global Energy Policy Series00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Before Oil -- t2. The Oil Age Arrives -- t3. The Big Payback -- t4. From Energy Poverty to Energy Extremism -- t5. Unnaturally Cool -- t6. We Have a Serious Problem -- t7. Iran and Dubai Lead the Way -- t8. Shifting Gears in Saudi Arabia -- t9. The Politics of Reform -- tConclusion: The Climate Hedge -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the discovery of oil in the 1930s, the Gulf monarchies—Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates, Oman, and Bahrain—went from being among the world’s poorest and most isolated places to some of its most ostentatiously wealthy. To maintain support, the ruling sheikhs provide their subjects with boundless cheap energy, unwittingly leading to some of the highest consumption rates on earth. Today, as summertime temperatures set new records, the Gulf’s rulers find themselves caught in a dilemma: can they curb their profligacy without jeopardizing the survival of some of the world’s last absolute monarchies?In Energy Kingdoms, Jim Krane takes readers inside these monarchies to consider their conundrum. He traces the history of the Gulf states’ energy use and policies, looking in particular at how energy subsidies have distorted demand. Oil exports are the lifeblood of their political-economic systems—and the basis of their strategic importance—but domestic consumption has begun eating into exports while climate change threatens to render their desert region uninhabitable. At risk are the sheikhdoms’ way of life, their relations with their Western protectors, and their political stability in a chaotic region. Backed by rich fieldwork and deep knowledge of the region, Krane expertly lays out the hard choices that Gulf leaders face to keep their states viable.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEnergy consumptionzPersian Gulf Region. 0aEnergy policyzPersian Gulf Region. 0aErdölindustrie. 0aPetroleum industry and tradexPolitical aspectszPersian Gulf Region. 0aPetroleum industry and tradezPersian Gulf Region. 0aSozialgeschichte. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/kran1793040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548922.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGb2019  a978-3-11-061076-5  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishb2019 